## Cross-Cutting Concerns

These behaviors apply across all 6 flows:

### LLM Resilience

All LLM calls route through the central gateway. When a provider's rate limit is hit, the system automatically falls back (e.g., Gemini → Mistral → local LLM). The actual provider used is logged in provenance. Deterministic calls (temperature=0) are cached to avoid duplicate quota consumption.

### Data Freshness Awareness

Every tool result includes a freshness indicator. When data is older than 12 months, agents include a staleness warning in their output: "⚠ This 10-K is from FY2022 — consider requesting updated filings." The report footer shows the oldest data point's date.

### Local LLM Reliability

When agents are routed to local LLMs, tool schemas are injected as ReAct-style instructions. If the local model produces malformed JSON tool calls, the system attempts JSON repair before falling back to cloud. Complex reasoning agents (DCF/LBO modeling, IC memo synthesis) are always routed to cloud or large local models (14B+).

### Iterative Tool Research

Agents can perform up to 3 rounds of tool calls per task. Each round's results are accumulated and passed to the next. This enables multi-hop research: "found revenue → need EBITDA margins → found margins → noticed a discrepancy → search for explanation." The iteration count and all intermediate results are captured in provenance.

### Graceful Degradation

If the real-time cache (Redis) is unavailable during workflow execution, provenance records are buffered in-memory on the agent process and flushed directly to the long-term store (PostgreSQL) on workflow completion. Users experience no data loss, but real-time provenance drill-down in the monitoring dashboard will be temporarily unavailable until the cache recovers. All other flows (agent execution, scoring, report generation) continue unaffected.

